</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:14:"Ben Greenfield";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:14:"ben-greenfield";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-07 11:59:01";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-07 15:59:01";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=268";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:26;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"292";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 22:22:53";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 22:22:53";s:12:"post_content";s:1217:"<div>Ben was born and raised in northern Vermont, where he currently runs a small-scale, diversified hill farm with his family. He lives with his wife and two sons in a self-built home that is powered by a windmill and solar photovoltaic panels. His work has appeared in numerous national periodicals, including the New York Times Magazine, Wired, Gourmet, Discover, Skiing, Eating Well, Yankee Magazine, Powder, Men‚Äôs Journal, National Geographic Adventure, and Outside.</div>
<div>His most recent book is Making Supper Safe: One Man‚Äôs Quest to Learn the Truth About Food Safety (Rodale). It was published on June 7, 2011. From dumpster diving, to the battle over food rights, to genetically engineered salmon and the interplay between humans and the bacteria they consume, Ben explores the untold story of food safety with humor and good-natured skepticism.</div>
<div>His first book, The Town That Food Saved: How One Community Found Vitality in Local Food (Rodale), was published in 2010. It tells the story of a rural, working-class Vermont community that is attempting to blueprint and implement a localized food system. The paperback edition will be released in conjunction with Making Supper Safe.</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:10:"Ben Hewitt";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:10:"ben-hewitt";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-07 12:01:52";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-07 16:01:52";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=292";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:27;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"434";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 04:03:29";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 04:03:29";s:12:"post_content";s:584:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>
<div>Ben Ratliff was born in 1968 in Manhattan and grew up in London and Rockland County, N.Y. He has been a jazz and pop critic for The New York Times since 1996, and lives with his wife and two sons in Manhattan.</div>
<div></div>
<div>He has written three books: <em>The Jazz Ear: Conversations Over Music </em>(2008); <em>Coltrane: The Story of a Sound</em> (2007, finalist for the National Book Critics Circle Award); and <em>Jazz: A Critic‚Äôs Guide to the 100 Most Important Recordings</em> (2002).</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:11:"Ben Ratliff";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:11:"ben-ratliff";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-07 12:06:30";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-07 16:06:30";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=434";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:28;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"511";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 13:54:11";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 13:54:11";s:12:"post_content";s:3785:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>Ben Stein (Benjamin J. Stein) was born November 25, 1944 in Washington, D.C., (He is the son of the economist and writer Herbert Stein) grew up in Silver Spring, Maryland, and attended Montgomery Blair High School. He graduated from Columbia University in 1966 with honors in economics. He graduated from Yale Law School in 1970 as valedictorian of his class by election of his classmates. He also studied in the graduate school of economics at Yale. He has worked as an economist at The Department of Commerce, a poverty lawyer in New Haven and Washington, D.C., a trial lawyer in the field of trade regulation at the Federal Trade Commission in Washington, D.C., a university adjunct at American University in Washington, D.C., at the University of California at Santa Cruz, and at Pepperdine University in Malibu, CA. At American U., he taught about the political and social content of mass culture. He taught the same subject at UCSC, as well as about political and civil rights under the Constitution. At Pepperdine, he has taught about libel law and about securities law and ethical issues since 1986.</div>
<div></div>
<div>In 1973 and 1974, he was a speech writer and lawyer for Richard Nixon at The White House and then for Gerald Ford. (He did NOT write the line, "I am not a crook.") He has been a columnist and editorial writer for The Wall Street Journal, a syndicated columnist for The Los Angeles Herald Examiner (R.I.P.) and King Features Syndicate, and a frequent contributor to Barrons, where his articles about the ethics of management buyouts and issues of fraud in the Milken Drexel junk bond scheme drew major national attention. He has been a regular columnist for Los Angeles Magazine, New York Magazine, E! Online, and most of all, has written a lengthy diary for twenty years for The American Spectator. He currently writes a column for The New york Times Sunday Business Section and has for many years, a column about personal finance for Yahoo!, is a commentator for CBS Sunday Morning, and for Fox News.</div>
<div>He has written, co-written and published thirty books, including seven novels, largely about life in Los Angeles, and twenty-one nonfiction books, about finance and about ethical and social issue in finance, and also about the political and social content of mass culture. He has done pioneering work in uncovering the concealed messages of TV and in explaining how TV and movies get made. His titles include <em>A License to Steal</em>, <em>Michael Milken and the Conspiracy to Bilk the Nation, The View From Sunset Boulevard, Hollywood Days, Hollywood Nights, DREEMZ, Financial Passages</em>, and <em>Ludes</em>. His most recent books are the best selling humor self help series, <em>How To Ruin Your Life</em>. He has also been a longtime screenwriter, writing, among many other scripts (most of which were unmade ) the first draft of The Boost, a movie based on Ludes, and the outlines of the lengthy miniseries Amerika, and the acclaimed Murder in Mississippi. He was one of the creators of the well regarded comedy, Fernwood Tonight.</div>
<div></div>
<div>He is also an extremely well known actor in movies, TV, and commercials. His part of the boring teacher in Ferris Bueller's Day Off was recently ranked as one of the fifty most famous scenes in American film. From 1997 to 2002, he was the host of the Comedy Central quiz show, "Win Ben Stein's Money." The show has won seven Emmies. He was a judge on CBS's Star Search, and on VH-1's "America's Most Smartest Model."</div>
<div></div>
<div>He lives with his wife, Alexandra Denman (former lawyer,) six cats and three large dogs in Beverly Hills. He is active in pro-animal and pro-life charitable events.</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:9:"Ben Stein";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:9:"ben-stein";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-07 12:11:17";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-07 16:11:17";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=511";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:29;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"207";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 15:06:46";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 15:06:46";s:12:"post_content";s:1621:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>

Bert Decker is a best selling author, entrepreneur, and national communications expert, having founded the communications training company Decker Communications, Inc. He has been featured in the New York¬†Times, Business Week, 20/20, as well as being the communications commentator for the NBC TODAY Show for the Presidential Debates.¬† His many accomplishments include:
<ul>
	<li>Coach to Charles Schwab, U.S. Congresswoman Nancy Pelosi, former Mattel CEO's John Ammerman and Jill Barrad, Olympians Bonnie Blair and Tom Dolan, San Francisco¬†49er All-Pro Brent Jones, and dozens of other executives</li>
	<li>Founder, Chairman and CEO of Decker Communications, Inc., a leader in communications training and executive coaching</li>
	<li>Consultant to Siemens, State Farm, Schwab, Met Life, and many others</li>
	<li>Professional speaker and best selling author of <em>You've Got to Be Believed To Be Heard</em> and <em>Speaking With Bold Assurance</em></li>
	<li>Co-producer of an Academy Award documentary</li>
	<li>Entrepreneur, founder of four companies, Chairman of Bold Assurance Ministries, NBC TODAY Communications Expert commentator, Advisory Board Salvation Army</li>
</ul>
<div>

Dr. Norman Vincent Peale has said, "Communication is the sure way to motivate an audience or an individual to action. And Bert Decker really communicates. He lifts the mind and thereby upgrades performance." Ken Blanchard, Ph.D., co-author of <em>The One Minute Manager </em>added, "Decker Communications makes communicating come alive!"

</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:11:"Bert Decker";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:11:"bert-decker";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-05-29 17:10:24";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-29 21:10:24";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=207";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:30;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"211";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 15:18:01";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 15:18:01";s:12:"post_content";s:2105:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>As one of America‚Äôs youngest and brightest social entrepreneurs, Beth launched her first company at age 22, created a consulting firm focused on sustainability, and lectures worldwide about her journey from fashion designer to humanitarian.</div>
<div></div>
<div>From when she first spoke out against the human rights violations she witnessed in the fashion industry to launching RainTees ‚Äì an apparel collection she created that plants a tree for every item sold ‚Äì her remarkable career has captivated audiences at TEDx, The United Nations, Google, and Earth Day Network‚Äôs annual event attended by more than 200,000 people on the National Mall in Washington, DC.</div>
<div><em>Hemispheres Magazine</em> nominated Beth as a ‚Äúhero‚Äù for her environmental achievements, and celebrity photographer John Russo featured her in his book, 100 Making a Difference, alongside Michelle Obama and Steven Spielberg.¬† L‚ÄôOreal selected her as a spokeswoman for Kiehl‚Äôs 100% natural skincare product and National Geographic, Glamour, People, In Style, and many other top-tier publications have featured Beth‚Äôs work.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Beth‚Äôs reforestation initiatives with RainTees also led her to work with indigenous cultures across Africa, the Amazon, and Central America and spurred her involvement in the largest environmental court case in history, where billions of gallons of toxic waste were dumped on tribal land in the Amazon by a multinational oil company. Her experiences inspired her to write a children‚Äôs book entitled From the Jungle (2012), which tells the story of the lives and journeys of four children living in endangered tropical rain forests. From the Jungle shows how we can change the world when we put people before profit and follow our passion.</div>
<div><em>‚ÄúBeth is an incredibly inspiring speaker and her extensive knowledge and understanding of the issues we face globally is clear through the profound work she is doing. Her passion is contagious.‚Äù
</em>‚Äî Scott Simpson, Google</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:10:"Beth Doane";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:10:"beth-doane";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-07 12:14:04";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-07 16:14:04";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=211";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:31;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"976";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"3";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-05-02 17:14:22";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-02 17:14:22";s:12:"post_content";s:4074:"Nevada‚Äôs longest serving Governor, Bob Miller has spoken domestically and internationally on tourism as an economic engine for governments, and on topics facing the nation‚Äôs state governments. He has served in various offices of the National Governors Association, including as Chairman from 1996-1997, and was appointed by President Clinton to the Advisory Commission on Intergovernmental Relations from 1993-1998. Having served as a police officer, police attorney, deputy district attorney, justice of the peace and elected district attorney in Las Vegas, he was also selected in 1982 as one of nine members of President Regan‚Äôs Task Force on Victims of Crime.Miller was selected by his peers to serve as President of the National District Attorneys Association during the term 1983-1984.¬† A recognized expert on the issue, he has spoken frequently about the need for criminal justice reforms.

&nbsp;

Born in Chicago, Illinois, Bob Miller arrived in Las Vegas with his family at age 10‚Äîlong before the city was recognizable as the place it is today. The son of a gaming pioneer‚Äîwho started out as bookmaker and business acquaintance of some very dubious criminal types and ended up a respectable businessman and a partner and eventually Chairman of the Board of the Riviera Hotel and Casino‚ÄîMiller was directed away from the glamor of Las Vegas tourism toward a more traditional upbringing and an early career in law enforcement.

&nbsp;

While studying law at Loyola Law School, Miller worked during consecutive summers as a police officer for the Los Angeles and Las Vegas Sheriff‚Äôs offices, returning after graduation to Las Vegas to help enable the launch of the Las Vegas Metropolitan Police Department. After joining the District Attorney‚Äôs Office, and later as a lower court judge, Miller became especially aware of the trauma of child abuse and the disparity between the rights of the accused with those of the victim. Mr. Miller went on to serve as Clark County‚Äôs District Attorney, and then on to the state capital as Lieutenant Governor of Nevada.

&nbsp;

Miller became Governor of Nevada in 1989. During his ten years in office, he transformed the Nevada economy by paving the way for infrastructure improvements‚Äîallowing for the construction of twenty of the largest hotels ever built; achieved a more efficient government while at the same time promoting more women to executive manager levels than any predecessor; and led the movement for Las Vegas to become the meeting capital of the world. During Miller‚Äôs term, the convention capacity of Nevada grew from just under one million to over seven million square feet‚Äîand by the time he left office in 1999, Nevada was served via non-stop air by foreign carriers from Tokyo, Hong Kong, Frankfurt, Dusseldorf, Cologne, Brussels, London, Manchester, Mexico City and all major cities in Canada.

&nbsp;

After leaving office, Mr. Miller specialized in business-to-public-sector relationship-building at all levels of government. He was invited by President Clinton to serve as Ambassador to Argentina, a post he declined for his family, and was placed by the U.S. State Department in select technical assistance consultations with the economic and finance ministries of countries including the republics of Bulgaria, Georgia and the Russian Federation. After helping persuade Clinton to be the first U.S. President to visit Bulgaria, Miller was designated Honorary Consul General for the Republic of Bulgaria.

&nbsp;

Miller is a past president of the International Association of Gaming Advisors (IAGA) and has spoken internationally, at the Russian real estate market conference in Moscow (2007), as well as at numerous tourism conferences and gaming conferences in Bulgaria. He is married with three children, the eldest of whom is Ross Miller, the current Secretary of State of Nevada. Miller holds a juris doctorate degree from Loyola Law School, and a bachelor of arts in political science from Santa Clara University, as well as several honorary degrees.";s:10:"post_title";s:10:"Bob Miller";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:10:"bob-miller";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-05-02 17:14:22";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-02 17:14:22";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=976";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:32;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"398";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:20:34";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:20:34";s:12:"post_content";s:2976:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>
<div>Bob Newhart has had a celebrated career in comedy, from the success of shows like ‚ÄúThe Bob Newhart Show‚Äù to his induction into the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences Hall of Fame. Famous for his one-man telephone conversations, Newhart appeals to all generations.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Newhart started out as the copywriter for an advertising agency, also working as an accountant on the side. He used to keep himself entertained at work by joking around with a friend‚Äîthey would make long phone calls to each other and recorded these antics as audition tapes. Although his friend eventually stopped, Newhart continued the prank phone calls by himself. This was the birth of his trademark one-man phone act.</div>
<div></div>
<div>In 1959, a Chicago deejay introduced him to the head of talent at Warner Bros. Records, and he was signed onto their label immediately. His first album, ‚ÄúThe Button-Down Mind of Bob Newhart,‚Äù became the first comedy album to go to the top of the charts. It won the ‚ÄúAlbum of the Year‚Äù Award at the 1961 Grammys, and Newhart was named ‚ÄúArtist of the Year.‚Äù He released seven more albums, each of them selling into the millions.</div>
<div></div>
<div>His first show was a variety show on CBS, which earned him a Peabody Award and an Emmy nomination in its first season. In 1972, CBS aired the premier of Newhart‚Äôs first sitcom series, ‚ÄúThe Bob Newhart Show,‚Äù co-starring Suzanne Pleshette. The show continued successfully for six years, featuring a large, talented cast of comics and actors.</div>
<div></div>
<div>During the success of ‚ÄúThe Bob Newhart Show,‚Äù Newhart starred in Hollywood hits such as Hell is for Heroes, On a Clear Day You Can See Forever, Catch 22, Little Miss Marker, Hot Millions, Cold Turkey, Thursday‚Äôs Game, and First Family opposite big Hollywood names.</div>
<div></div>
<div>After the end of ‚ÄúThe Bob Newhart Show,‚Äù Newhart toured around the country for four years, performing live stand-up comedy onstage. In 1982, Newhart returned to CBS with ‚ÄúNewhart,‚Äù which was immensely successful for eight seasons. Newhart decided to cut the series short, opting to end the series during the peak of its success. Since then, he has been in a number of movies, such as ‚ÄúElf‚Äù (2003) and hit TV-series, such as ‚ÄúER‚Äù and ‚ÄúDesperate Housewives.‚Äù</div>
<div></div>
<div>Newhart‚Äôs other achievements include his selection as Grand Marshall of the 102 Tournament of Roses Parade. ‚ÄúThe Button Down Mind of Bob Newhart‚Äù was added to the Library of Congress‚Äô 2006 National Recording Registry, and Bob Newhart was inducted into the National Association of Broadcasters‚Äô Hall of Fame in 2009.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Newhart lives with his wife and four children in California. He continues to put on shows throughout the country and still occasionally stars in Hollywood movies.</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:11:"Bob Newhart";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:11:"bob-newhart";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:20:34";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:20:34";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=398";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:33;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"592";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-12-18 18:04:51";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-12-18 18:04:51";s:12:"post_content";s:1959:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>
<div>Bob Woodward is regarded as one of America‚Äôs preeminent investigative reporters and non-fiction authors. He has worked for The Washington Post since 1971 as a reporter, and is currently an associate editor of the Post. While a young reporter for The Washington Post in 1972, Woodward was teamed up with Carl Bernstein; the two did much, but not all, of the original news reporting on the Watergate scandal that led to numerous government investigations and the eventual resignation of President Richard Nixon. Gene Roberts, former managing editor of The New York Times has called the work of Woodward and Bernstein ‚Äúmaybe the single greatest reporting effort of all time.‚Äù</div>
<div></div>
<div>Woodward has authored or coauthored 15 non-fiction books in the last 35 years. All 15 have been national bestsellers and 11 of them have been #1 national non-fiction bestsellers ‚Äî more #1 national non-fiction bestsellers than any contemporary author. He has written multiple #1 national non-fiction bestsellers on a wide range of subjects in each of the four decades he has been active as an author, from 1974 to 2009.</div>
<div></div>
<div>He has been a recipient of nearly every other major American journalism award, including the Heywood Broun award (1972), Worth Bingham Prize for Investigative Reporting (1972 and 1986), Sigma Delta Chi Award (1973), George Polk Award (1972), William Allen White Medal (2000), and the Gerald R. Ford Prize for Reporting on the Presidency (2002). Fred Barnes of The Weekly Standard called Woodward ‚Äúthe best pure reporter of his generation, perhaps ever.‚Äù¬† In 2003, Albert Hunt of The Wall Street Journal called Woodward ‚Äúthe most celebrated journalist of our age.‚Äù In 2004, Bob Schieffer of CBS News said, ‚ÄúWoodward has established himself as the best reporter of our time. He may be the best reporter of all time.‚Äù</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:12:"Bob Woodward";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:12:"bob-woodward";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2012-12-18 18:04:51";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2012-12-18 18:04:51";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=592";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:34;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"188";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 14:35:48";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 14:35:48";s:12:"post_content";s:3034:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>
<div>Brad Cohen presents an inspiring true story of incredible challenges and unwavering determination. Featured on Oprah, People Magazine and a Hallmark Hall of Fame movie titled: Front of the Class. This story is one about following your dreams despite the challenges that are placed in front of you.¬† As a child with Tourette syndrome, a neurological brain disorder that causes the body to make strange sounds and uncontrollable violent twitches, Brad was beaten, mocked, and shunned. As an adult, Brad overcame all odds to become an award-winning teacher of the year for the state of Georgia. The road in between was a roller coaster ride in perseverance. Brad Cohen inspires audiences to overcome life‚Äôs challenges and pursue their goals.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Even today Brad is ejected from movie theaters and restaurants. Nothing has stopped him from taking leadership roles in a variety of settings and being a role model for others. This story of personal challenge and unwavering determination proves anyone can make their dreams come true. No one can hear Brad‚Äôs story and fail to see the power of a positive attitude.Brad is from Atlanta, Georgia and is an Area Lead Teacher for Cobb County Schools. He is responsible for teaching the teachers.¬† Prior to that he taught 2nd grade, 3rd grade, and was a technology lab teacher.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Brad has served as Vice President of the Board of Governors for the Tourette Syndrome Association of Georgia, and also founded an overnight camp for children with Tourette syndrome. Part of Brad‚Äôs past included being the team mascot ‚ÄúHomer‚Äù for the Atlanta Braves Baseball team.</div>
<div></div>
<div>A native of St. Louis, he has a bachelor‚Äôs degree from Bradley University (Peoria, IL), where he graduated cum laude with honors and received their Outstanding Young Alumnus Award. Brad has earned master‚Äôs and specialist‚Äôs degrees from Georgia State University, and graduated from both the Gwinnett County Leadership Academy for aspiring school administrators and Cobb County‚Äôs Leadership Academy.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Brad has received many other awards, including St. Louis Area United Way Volunteer of the Month; he was a Ben &amp; Jerry‚Äôs Citizen Cool semifinalist; and he was recognized by the Atlanta Braves and BellSouth with an Excellence in Education award. Brad recently got married to his wife Nancy and still works with the community.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Brad was featured on Oprah, People Magazine and Inside Edition after the release of his award-winning book, <em>Front of the Class: How Tourette Syndrome Made Me the Teacher I Never Had</em>.¬† His book was named the ‚ÄúEducation Book of the Year‚Äù for the Independent Book Publishers.¬† CBS featured Brad‚Äôs ‚ÄúHallmark Hall of Fame‚Äù movie about his life in December 2008.¬† He is now a motivational speaker and inspires people to keep a positive attitude and to follow their dreams.</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:10:"Brad Cohen";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:10:"brad-cohen";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-05-29 15:27:06";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-29 19:27:06";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=188";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:35;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:4:"1144";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"6";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-06-20 16:21:43";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 20:21:43";s:12:"post_content";s:1323:"<p style="text-align: left;">A writer and filmmaker who received his Ph.D. in English at Case Western Reserve University, Brad Ricca is currently a SAGES fellow who teaches classes on comics, popular culture, and narrative biography. His latest book is the first literary biography of the creators of Superman, <i>Super Boys: The Amazing Adventures of Jerry Siegel &amp; Joe Shuster ‚Äì The Creators of Superman</i> which draws on nearly ten years of research in dusty libraries and secret comics hoards to portray two teenagers who, in the midst of the Great Depression, created a global icon.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">A lifelong comics nerd and aficionado, Ricca has spoken about comics in <i>The Wall Street Journal</i>, <i>The New York Times</i>, <i>Christian Science Monitor, The Boston Globe, </i>and on NPR‚Äôs ‚ÄúAll Things Considered.‚Äù He has given talks at The Maltz Museum of Jewish History<i> </i>and the legendary San Diego Comic-Con, along with numerous schools and conferences from Oxford to Kyoto.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Ricca won the St. Lawrence Book Award for his first book of poetry, <i>American Mastodon</i>, and is also an independent filmmaker whose documentary, Last Son, screened all over the world and won a Silver Ace Award at the Las Vegas International Film Festival.</p>";s:10:"post_title";s:10:"Brad Ricca";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:10:"brad-ricca";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-25 09:53:30";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-25 13:53:30";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:63:"http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=1144";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:36;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"560";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-12-18 16:54:31";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-12-18 16:54:31";s:12:"post_content";s:1863:"Brandon Webb is a former U.S. Navy SEAL with combat deployments to southwest Asia, including Iraq, and Afghanistan. His proudest accomplishment in the US Military was his role as Course Manager for the elite US Navy SEAL Sniper program.¬† This is arguably one of the best and most difficult sniper qualification courses in the world.
Webb has received numerous distinguished service awards throughout his career including the Presidential Unit Citation (personally given to him by President George W. Bush) awarded to his SEAL platoon after their Sept 11th, 2001 deployment to Afghanistan.
After the Navy he worked briefly with a three letter agency overseas, then left to focus on other work within the Defense Industry.
He was formerly a contributing editor for Military.com and now heads up SOFREP.com (Special Operations Forces Situation Report) as the Editor-in-Chief. SOFREP is the number one site for timely and accurate information regarding the Special Operations community globally. As a former Navy SEAL and Editor of SOFREP.com he is regularly featured in the national and international media for his Special Operations industry expertise.
Brandon's writing has been featured in both print magazines and blogs world-wide.¬† He is author of The Red Circle (St. Martin's Press) and co-author of Navy SEAL Sniper (Skyhorse Publishing).
Webb enjoys speaking with professional organizations of all sizes.¬† His main topics have to do with over coming adversity, mental toughness, leadership and the dedication and drive it takes to make it through one of the toughest Special Operations training programs in the world.
He is an avid surfer (and member of the legendary Windansea surf club), free diver, private pilot and open ocean swimmer.¬† When he's not in the water or airborne, he splits his time between Lake Tahoe, NV and La Jolla, California.";s:10:"post_title";s:12:"Brandon Webb";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:12:"brandon-webb";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-07 12:25:11";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-07 16:25:11";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=560";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:37;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"145";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-12 22:43:13";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-12 22:43:13";s:12:"post_content";s:1307:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
