DAVID POYER is a retired naval officer and the most popular living author of American sea fiction. He has published almost 30 novels since 1976.

Poyer is best known for his naval fiction series. His most popular series follow the career and adventures of US Navy officer Dan Lenson. Another series follows the adventures of ex-Coast Guard commercial diver Lyle ‚ÄúTiller‚Äù Galloway. His writing has been compared to that of Joseph Conrad and Herman Wouk and some of his novels are required reading at Annapolis.

Material for his books is drawn from Poyer‚Äôs career in the military. He graduated from the US Naval Academy in 1971 and served as a naval officer and reserve caption in the Atlantic, Arctic, Pacific, Caribbean, and Persian Gulf until his retirement in 2001.

Poyer‚Äôs work includes alternative history and science fiction written under the pseudonym David Andreissen. He currently teaches at the Wilkes University MA/MFA program in Creative Writing in Pennsylvania. He lives with his wife Lenore Hart and their daughter on Virginia‚Äôs Eastern Shore.

</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:11:"David Poyer";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:11:"david-poyer";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 09:59:11";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 13:59:11";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=425";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:71;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"452";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 04:26:34";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 04:26:34";s:12:"post_content";s:1286:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>
<div>

David Rosenfelt is the Edgar-nominated author of the Andy Carpenter mystery series, praised as ‚Äú<em>a blessed anomaly in crime fiction‚Äù (Booklist). </em>He is also the writer of three TV movies, and founder of the Tara Foundation, which has saved 4,000 dogs.

<em>Rosenfelt</em> graduated from <em>New York University with the goal of entering the movie business. He took a job with his uncle, then President of United Artists, </em>and made his way up to a position as President of Marketing for Tri-Star Pictures, where he worked on films including <em>Rocky</em>, <em>The Natural</em>, and <em>Rambo</em>.

When Rosenfelt decided to leave the movie business and try his hand at writing, he wrote and sold several feature films and saw a few of his TV movies to the small screen. He completed his first novel <em>Open and Shut </em>in 2002, and has since written eleven novels, most of which feature Andy Carpenter, an attorney and dog lover whose affection for dogs often helps him solve mysteries.

In 1995, David and his wife started the Tara Foundation to find loving homes for dogs. They bring home the dogs that are too old or ill to be adopted, and currently live with 27 dogs.

</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:15:"David Rosenfelt";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:15:"david-rosenfelt";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 10:05:48";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 14:05:48";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=452";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:72;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"590";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-12-18 18:02:59";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-12-18 18:02:59";s:12:"post_content";s:571:"Author, speaker, and humorist David Wood is a former stand-up comedian with several David Letterman Show appearances under his belt. He has performed everywhere from Caesars Palace to corporation keynotes and employee meetings. A few years ago, he took a one year sabbatical to travel to exotic locales around-the-world. He turned that adventure into¬†the highly entertaining book <em>Around the World in 80 Rounds</em>.¬†David was also the founder of Right Brain Business Training, a Seattle-based company which produces humorous employee training videos sold worldwide.";s:10:"post_title";s:10:"David Wood";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:10:"david-wood";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2012-12-18 18:02:59";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2012-12-18 18:02:59";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=590";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:73;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"104";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-12 21:04:40";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-12 21:04:40";s:12:"post_content";s:2849:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>
<div>Dick Armey was a member of the House of Representatives for eighteen years, acting as the House Majority Leader from 1995 to 2003. Since 2003, he has been the chairman of FreedomWorks, a non-profit organization based in Washington D.C. that fights for less government and lower taxes.</div>
<div></div>
<div>After receiving his Ph.D in economics from the University of Oklahoma, Armey began his teaching career at the University of Montana. Armey became the chairman of the economics department at the University of North Texas in 1977, exposing him to a more ‚Äúpolitical‚Äù environment.</div>
<div></div>
<div>He was first elected to Congress in 1984, and quickly solidified a reputation for himself in Washington as a conservative member dedicated to good public policy. After winning re-election in 1986, he had his first legislative victory: the passage of an amendment with Congressman Jack Kemp and Delegate Walter Fauntroy to reform public housing.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Also during this second term, Armey passed landmark legislation that propelled him to national recognition‚Äîhe collaborated with key Democrats and fought against the Reagan Defense Department to pass legislation to close down obsolete military bases. As a result, more than 100 obsolete bases are being closed, saving taxpayers more than $4 billion a year.</div>
<div></div>
<div>The Wall Street Journal wrote in 1988, ‚ÄúBy tempering his tactics without abandoning his goals, [Armey] is getting legislation passed.‚Äù</div>
<div></div>
<div>Armey‚Äôs next goal was to fight federal farm reforms in 1990. Along with other conservative Republicans, he teamed up with urban liberals like Charles Schumer and Barney Frank to form a bipartisan coalition, pressuring agricultural committees to bring forward leaner bills. Their efforts laid the groundwork for the free market reforms in the 1996 Freedom to Farm legislation.</div>
<div></div>
<div>In January 1991, Armey was appointed ranking Republican on the Joint Economic Committee after leading the opposition to President Bush‚Äôs tax increases. He decided to run for Conference Chairman in June of 1992, and was elected in December of the same year.</div>
<div></div>
<div>In 1994, he was the main author of the republican Contract with America‚Äîa list of ten bills that Republicans would bring up for vote during the first 100 days of a Republican-controlled Congress. The Contract was a success, and the Republicans controlled the House for the first time in 40 years. Armey became the Majority Leader of the 104th Congress.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Armey has written four books: <em>Price Theory: A Policy--Welfare Approach</em>; <em>The Freedom Revolution</em>; <em>The Flat Tax</em>; and <em>Armey‚Äôs Axioms</em>.</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:10:"Dick Armey";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:10:"dick-armey";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 10:14:47";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 14:14:47";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=104";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:74;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"496";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 13:27:35";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 13:27:35";s:12:"post_content";s:1729:"Dorothy Clay Sims, Esq. is the well-known member of the now legendary Casey Anthony defense team. ¬†Sims is recognized for her frequent compassionate presence in worldwide media conferring with her client who was charged with the murder of her 2-year-old daughter ‚Äî ¬†and who helped to obtain Casey Anthony‚Äôs not guilty verdict in the famous 2011 trial. ¬†The celebrated and much sought after attorney is the founder of the Florida-based law firm, Sims and Stakenborg, P.A. She wrote the¬†best selling book, ‚ÄúExposing the Deceptive Defense Doctor,‚Äù a consistent top seller among attorneys and other experts. Sims has been interviewed in numerous broadcast and print media including Greta Van Susteren‚Äôs ‚ÄúOn The Record‚Äù (Fox), CNN‚Äôs ‚ÄúPiers Morgan Show,‚Äù ‚ÄúCNN‚Äôs Headline News‚Äù (HLN) and the international news radio outlet, Voice of America. She has been interviewed in publications such as<span style="text-decoration: underline;"> National Law Journal</span>, <span style="text-decoration: underline;">Wall Street Journal</span>, the<span style="text-decoration: underline;"> New York Times</span>, and <span style="text-decoration: underline;">Lawyers USA</span>. ¬†Sims‚Äô grandfather, the trial lawyer John Y. Brown, Sr., was the former U.S. congressman and speaker of the Kentucky House of Representatives who introduced one of the South‚Äôs first civil rights bills. ¬†Sims, who is on a mission to educate the public about how forensic issues are applied and misused in the courtroom, is currently working on a documentary and is co-author of a book on the same topic. ¬†Sims is frequently invited to speak with legal and medical organizations and has given over 300 speeches nationwide and abroad.";s:10:"post_title";s:17:"Dorothy Clay Sims";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:17:"dorothy-clay-sims";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 10:24:46";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 14:24:46";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=496";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:75;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"577";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-12-18 17:36:13";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-12-18 17:36:13";s:12:"post_content";s:3014:"Dr. Leana Wen is a physician at Harvard and Brigham &amp; Women‚Äôs Hospital/Massachusetts General Hospital and a former Rhodes Scholar. Inspired by her own childhood illness and then her mother‚Äôs long battle with cancer, Dr. Wen is passionate about guiding patients to advocate for better care. She has been featured in <em>TIME</em>, <em>Newsweek</em>, ABC News, <em>The New York Times</em>, <em>The Washington Post</em>, <em>Teen Vogue</em>, and the award-winning HBO documentary, <em>Reporter</em>. A professional speaker for ten years, she is sought-after in the U.S. and around the world, with annual engagements throughout Europe, the Americas, Asia, and Africa.After finishing college at the age of 18, Dr. Wen graduated from Washington University School of Medicine and won the Rhodes Scholarship to study at the University of Oxford. She received her residency training in emergency medicine at Harvard at the Brigham &amp; Women‚Äôs Hospital and Massachusetts General Hospital, and has been a fellow and consultant to the World Health Organization, the Brookings Institution, Eurasia Group, and China Medical Board. Dr. Wen has served as the National President of the American Medical Student Association and the President of the American Academy of Emergency Medicine Resident and Student Association. Recognized for her leadership in national and international health, she was selected as Chair of the Young Professionals Commission, a group of 25 young health professionals chosen from around the world to re-envision global health professional education. In 2007, she was also selected by the Secretary of Health and Human Services to represent physicians-in-training on the Council on Graduate Medical Education, an advisory commission to Congress. An active researcher in better ways to improve patient-physician communication, Dr. Wen has received grant support from the National Institutes of Health, the Beckman Foundation, the American College of Emergency Physicians, and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute. She has published in numerous scientific publications including <em>The Lancet</em>, <em>JAMA: The Journal of the American Medical Association</em>, and <em>Annals of Emergency Medicine</em>, and has served as a regular columnist for news outlets including <em>The New Physician</em>, <em>Common Sense</em>, and Medscape.com. With journalist Nick Kristof, she wrote a <a href="http://twofortheroad.blogs.nytimes.com/">blog for <em>The New York Times</em></a>, along with articles in <em>The Washington Post</em>, the <em>St. Louis Post-Dispatch</em>, <em>Worth</em> magazine, and others. She is the co-author of a book on the importance of patient advocacy in healthcare reform, <em>When¬†Doctors Don't Listen: How to Avoid Misdiagnoses and Unnecessary Tests</em>.

Wen lives in Boston. Along with her husband Sebastian, a native of South Africa, she travels regularly between five continents to speak about simple yet effective ways for patients to take control of their health.";s:10:"post_title";s:13:"Dr. Leana Wen";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:64:"dr-leana-wenphysician-award-winning-author-international-speaker";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 10:30:50";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 14:30:50";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=577";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:76;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"240";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 16:13:56";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 16:13:56";s:12:"post_content";s:1517:"Dr. Nathaniel Frank is author of¬†<em>Unfriendly Fire: How the Gay Ban Undermines the Military and Weakens America</em> (March 2009). He¬†earned his Ph.D. and M.A. in History at Brown University. Dr. Frank is Senior Research Fellow at the Palm Center at the University of California, Santa Barbara and teaches history on the adjunct faculty at New York University's Gallatin School.

His book, drawing on hundreds of exclusive interviews, presents the latest research and over a decade of evidence on gay service showing that gays can and do serve openly in the U.S. military without incident, and that the policy itself is weakening the military it was supposed to protect.

Dr. Frank‚Äôs publications on gays in the military and other topics have appeared in The New York Times, the Washington Post, The New Republic, Slate, Los Angeles Times, Huffington Post, Newsday, Philadelphia Inquirer, and Lingua Franca<em>,</em> among others.¬† He has been interviewed for national television and radio programs, including ABC‚Äôs Good Morning America, the CBS Evening News with Dan Rather, CNN‚Äôs Anderson Cooper 360, CBS News on Logo, the BBC and MSNBC‚Äôs Abrams Report.

He has also consulted with ABC‚Äôs 20/20 and CBS‚Äôs 60 Minutes. Dr. Frank‚Äôs research and opinions have been cited on the Congressional floor, in syndicated columns, in the blogosphere, the New York Post, The Advocate, National Review Online, the AP and other venues, including college syllabi and media roundups. He lives in Brooklyn, NY.";s:10:"post_title";s:19:"Dr. Nathaniel Frank";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:18:"dr-nathaniel-frank";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 10:42:04";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 14:42:04";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=240";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:77;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"596";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-12-18 18:16:15";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-12-18 18:16:15";s:12:"post_content";s:2366:"Dr. Robin Zasio, Psy. D., LCSW,¬†is a featured doctor on the Emmy-nominated A&amp;E hit series <em>Hoarders</em>, the host of Animal Planet‚Äôs <em>My Extreme Animal Phobia</em>, and the author of <em>The Hoarder in You: How to Live a Happier, Healthier, Uncluttered Life</em>. A licensed clinical psychologist and a licensed clinical social worker, Dr. Zasio has specialized in treating anxiety and related disorders for the past¬†20 years utilizing Cognitive Behavioral Therapy and Exposure and Response Prevention techniques. Dr. Zasio has been speaking at professional conferences for 15 years on anxiety and related conditions, and is asked to speak regularly for many network shows including the <em>Today</em> show, <em>Good Day New York</em>, <em>Good Day Sacramento</em>, and HLN‚Äôs <em>Jane Velez-Mitchell</em>. She has been a guest expert on <em>The Nate Berkus Show</em> and <em>The Rosie O‚ÄôDonnell Show</em>, and has done numerous interviews for magazines and newspapers all over the country.After developing a thriving private practice, she founded The Anxiety Treatment Center of Sacramento in 2005, and more recently, The¬†Cognitive Behavior Therapy Center, and The Compulsive Hoarding Center, all¬†located in Sacramento, CA. She was also the co-creator of The Anxiety Treatment Center of Northern California, and the owner and operator of two mental health recovery homes.

Dr. Zasio¬†continues to maintain her private practice providing individual,¬†group and family therapy services, in addition to supervising interns who are learning to treat anxiety disorders.¬†She is the President of the OCD Sacramento Foundation, Inc., and has served as the President of the Sacramento Valley Psychological Association, currently¬†remaining on the board as their Continuing Education Chair¬†and Media Representative. She also serves on the Scientific Advisory Board and the Clinical Advisory Board for the International Obsessive Compulsive Disorder Foundation, and is a faculty member for their Behavior Therapy Training Institute. She writes a monthly "Doctor‚Äôs Column" for the¬†Sacramento Chapter of the National Alliance of the Mentally Ill¬†and is a member of the International Obsessive Compulsive Disorder Foundation, American Psychological Association, Trichotillomania Learning Center, and Association for Behavioral and Cognitive Therapies.";s:10:"post_title";s:15:"Dr. Robin Zasio";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:14:"dr-robin-zasio";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 10:54:28";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 14:54:28";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=596";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:78;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"264";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 16:55:40";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 16:55:40";s:12:"post_content";s:1128:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
