Ed Gray is the co-author of <em>In Nixon‚Äôs Web: A Year in the Crosshairs of Watergate</em>, his father L. Patrick Gray‚Äôs memoir of his year as acting director of the FBI immediately following the death of J. Edgar Hoover. Following his father‚Äôs death in 2005, Gray began looking into his father‚Äôs belief that the names - and especially the motives - of the actual anonymous sources of press leaks during that time had never been honestly identified. In presentations that have included Dartmouth College and the Nixon Presidential Library, Gray has led audiences through that quest for the truth, allowing them arrive at their own conclusions and speculations.

Gray, who at the time of Watergate was a junior naval officer in a highly classified job similar to the one held by Bob Woodward, met many of the players then. Others he came to know much later. In between, he founded, with his wife Rebecca, the esteemed <em>Gray‚Äôs Sporting Journal</em> and went on to his prolific career as a book author and magazine journalist.

</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:7:"Ed Gray";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:7:"ed-gray";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2012-11-13 16:55:40";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 16:55:40";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=264";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:79;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"270";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 21:30:52";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 21:30:52";s:12:"post_content";s:506:"Eliza Griswold, a fellow at the New America Foundation, received a 2010 Rome Prize from the American Academy in Rome. Her journalism has appeared in<em>The Atlantic</em>, <em>The New Yorker</em>, <em>The New York</em> <em>Times Magazine</em>, and <em>Harper‚Äôs Magazine</em>, among others. A 2007 Nieman Fellow at Harvard University, she was awarded the first Robert I. Friedman Award for investigative reporting. A collection of her poems, <em>Wideawake</em> <em>Field</em>, was published by FSG in 2007.";s:10:"post_title";s:14:"Eliza Griswold";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:14:"eliza-griswold";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 10:58:31";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 14:58:31";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=270";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:80;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"258";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 16:43:53";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 16:43:53";s:12:"post_content";s:589:"Emily Giffin is the New York Times bestselling author of <em>Something Borrowed</em>, <em>Something Blue, Baby Proof</em>, and <em>Love the One You‚Äôre With</em>. Among myriad praises, she‚Äôs been called "a dependably down-to-earth, girlfriendly storyteller" by The New York Times. Giffin is a graduate of Wake Forest University and the University of Virginia School of Law. After practicing litigation at a New York firm for several years, she moved to London to write full time. She now lives in Atlanta with her husband and three young children where she is working on her fifth book.";s:10:"post_title";s:12:"Emily Giffin";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:12:"emily-giffin";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 11:15:38";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 15:15:38";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=258";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:81;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"473";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 12:47:58";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 12:47:58";s:12:"post_content";s:2215:"Senior writer and terrorism correspondent for <em>The New York Times</em> Eric Schmitt has embedded with troops in Iraq, Afghanistan, Somalia, and Pakistan and has twice been a member of <em>Times</em> reporting teams that were awarded the Pulitzer Prize. He is co-author, with Thom Shanker, of <em>Counterstrike: The Untold Story of America‚Äôs Secret Campaign Against Al Qaeda</em>, and has written about the military and national security for <em>The Times</em> for more than 20 years. Mr. Schmitt first joined <em>The Times</em> in 1983, as the clerk for then senior columnist James Reston, and had several assignments before being appointed a Pentagon correspondent in 1990. He served as a Pentagon correspondent from 1990 to 1996, and then again from Sept. 11, 2001 until 2006, covering issues of national security. ¬†Between 1996 and 2001, he worked as a domestic correspondent covering, among other subjects, the Congress and immigration.During his tenure at <em>The Times</em>, Schmitt has covered some of the newspaper‚Äôs biggest stories, including the House and Senate impeachment proceedings against President Bill Clinton in 1999, the 1994 military landing with the Marines in Haiti, and the December 1992 military operation in Somalia. In 1991 he spent three months in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait covering the Persian Gulf War. He was part of the team of <em>New York Times</em> reporters awarded the Pulitzer for coverage of the transfer of sensitive military technology to China in 1999. In 2009, he shared another Pulitzer for coverage of Afghanistan and Pakistan. ¬†Before joining <em>The Times</em>, Mr. Schmitt was an education reporter at the <em>Tri-City Herald</em> in Kennewick, Washington. He received a B.A. in political science and third world development from Williams College in 1982. Schmitt was selected to attend Harvard University‚Äôs Executive Program on National and International Security in 1991 and was awarded a Knight Journalism Fellowship at Stanford University in the 2006-07 academic year. He is a member of the Council on Foreign Relations, and researched and wrote <em>Counterstrike</em> as a writer-in-residence with Thom Shanker at the Center for a New American Security.";s:10:"post_title";s:12:"Eric Schmitt";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:12:"eric-schmitt";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 11:27:02";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 15:27:02";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=473";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:82;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"498";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 13:30:22";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 13:30:22";s:12:"post_content";s:2381:"Eric Sinoway is an entrepreneur and seasoned executive with experience in for-profit, academic, and non-profit organizations. He is the cofounder and president of Axcess Worldwide, a New York-based partnership development company that creates inspired ideas and connects extraordinary brands and people. Axcess works with companies ranging from Rolls Royce and InterContinental Hotels &amp; Resorts to Target and Delta Air Lines. Eric‚Äôs speeches "to inspire the working professional" draw upon his book, <em>Howard‚Äôs Gift</em>, which he wrote in collaboration with iconic Harvard Business School professor Howard Stevenson. Sharing the framework he developed for <em>Howard‚Äôs Gift</em>, Eric leads audiences through a process called "Business Planning for Your Life‚Äôs Work," including thought tools that provide listeners with new ways to think about their lives and careers, and actionable ideas to unlock their full personal and professional potential. In a 20 to 60 minute speech or seminar, Eric conveys ways in which all of us can be entrepreneurial in our careers and lives, even if we aren‚Äôt entrepreneurs in the traditional sense. A captivating and inspirational speaker whose lectures, presentations, and seminars have broad appeal and wide applicability, Eric calls upon his unique personal and professional experiences‚Äîmixing humor, sincerity and real world anecdotes to resonate with working professionals, executives, students, and men and women of all ages. Eric also speaks on specific subject areas of expertise, including the topics of entrepreneurship, where he conveys lessons from experiences starting and working with a variety of early stage companies; organizational and fundraising effectiveness for non-profits and universities, where he shares his secrets of success as a fundraiser at Harvard and his work with the Arnold Schwarzenegger and Todd Wagner Foundations; and the burgeoning field of Partnership Development, which Eric is helping to define through his work as cofounder &amp; President of Axcess Worldwide, which is the world‚Äôs first Partnership Development company. Eric has spoken for trade conferences, private events, and universities, including NYU, Cornell, and Harvard. For multiple years he was a featured speaker at the national conference for the After School All-Stars, Arnold Schwarzenegger‚Äôs charitable foundation.";s:10:"post_title";s:12:"Eric Sinoway";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:12:"eric-sinoway";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 11:43:09";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 15:43:09";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=498";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:83;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"552";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-12-18 16:44:40";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-12-18 16:44:40";s:12:"post_content";s:2306:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
