Actor Gene Wilder is probably best remembered for his portrayal of Willy Wonka in the 1971 adaptation of the Roald Dahl novel, ‚ÄúWilly Wonka and the Chocolate Factory.‚Äù Born in Wisconsin, Gene studied drama at the University of Iowa before attending the Bristol Old Vic Theatre School. He made his Hollywood debut in 1967 with a small appearance in ‚ÄúBonnie and Clyde,‚Äù but his big break came when he starred in Mel Brook‚Äôs 1968 comedy, ‚ÄúThe Producers.‚Äù

Perhaps Gene‚Äôs best performances are in 1973‚Äôs ‚ÄúBlazing Saddles‚Äù and 1974‚Äôs ‚ÄúYoung Frankenstein,‚Äù both of which he collaborated on with director Mel Brooks. He also teamed up with actor Richard Pryor on multiple occasions, leading to a stint of comedies starring the pair, including the highly successful cult comedy, ‚ÄúStir Crazy.‚Äù

Gene wrote and directed multiple films, including 1977‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe World‚Äôs Greatest Lover‚Äù and 1979‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Frisco Kid.‚Äù He met his late wife, Gilda Radner, on the set of the 1982 movie, ‚ÄúHanky Panky.‚Äù They were married for five years until Gilda‚Äôs death in 1989 from ovarian cancer. After her death, Gene co-founded Gilda‚Äôs Club, a support group for victims of ovarian cancer, and supported the creation of the Gilda Radner Ovarian Cancer Detection Center in Los Angeles, CA.

In 1998, he collaborated on the book, <em>Gilda‚Äôs Disease</em>, with oncologist Steve Piver, furthering his dedication to the fight against ovarian cancer. He released his autobiography, <em>Kiss Me Like a Stranger: My Search for Love and Art, </em>in 2006 to much critical praise. He has recently published two novels, <em>The French Whore </em>(St. Martin‚Äôs Press, 2007) and <em>The Woman Who Wouldn‚Äôt </em>(St. Martin‚Äôs Griffin, 2009). Gene currently lives in Connecticut with his wife, Karen Boyer, and remains active in his charity work for ovarian cancer.

</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:11:"Gene Wilder";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:11:"gene-wilder";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 12:21:36";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 16:21:36";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=582";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:98;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"321";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 23:32:19";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 23:32:19";s:12:"post_content";s:545:"Glenn Kessler¬†is an acclaimed¬†diplomatic correspondent for The Washington Post and has been recipient of numerous awards, including two shared Pulitzer Prizes.¬†A member of the Council on Foreign Relations, he¬†has reported from dozens of countries and also has covered the White House and Congress.¬†Kessler is¬†the author of <em>The Confidante: Condoleezza Rice and the Creation of the Bush Legacy</em>. He is a graduate of Brown University and Columbia University's School of International and Public Affairs, and lives in McLean, Virginia.";s:10:"post_title";s:13:"Glenn Kessler";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:13:"glenn-kessler";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-20 12:30:42";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-20 16:30:42";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=321";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";