</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:11:"Keith Ablow";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:11:"keith-ablow";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-26 11:08:36";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-26 15:08:36";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:61:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=88";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:152;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"166";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 14:02:36";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 14:02:36";s:12:"post_content";s:3152:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>The New York Times hailed Ken Burns as ‚Äúthe most accomplished documentary filmmaker of his generation.‚Äù ‚ÄúMore Americans get their history from Ken Burns than any other source,‚Äù said late historian Stephen Ambrose. With almost twenty documentaries to his name, Ken has earned countless awards and nominations, ranging from Oscars to Peabodys.</div>
<div></div>
<div>His first feature film, ‚ÄúBrooklyn Bridge‚Äù (1981), about the heroic completion of the largest bridge of its era, was nominated for an Academy Award. He followed this early success with a string of several historical documentaries: ‚ÄúThe Shakers: Hands to Work, Hearts to God,‚Äù ‚ÄúStatue of Liberty,‚Äù ‚ÄúHuey Long,‚Äù ‚ÄúThe Congress,‚Äù and ‚ÄúThomas Hart Benton.‚Äù</div>
<div></div>
<div>In 1990, Ken Burns served as the director, producer, co-writer, chief cinematographer, music director and executive producer of the epic television series ‚ÄúThe Civil War,‚Äù which aired on PBS in nine episodes. ‚ÄúThe Civil War‚Äù was the highest rated television series in the history of American public television at the time, with an audience of 40 million during its premier. Columnist George Will said about the series, ‚ÄúIf better use has ever been made of television, I have not seen it and do not expect to see better until Ken Burns turns his prodigious talents to his next project.‚Äù The series was awarded with over 40 major film and television awards, including two Emmy Awards, two Grammys Awards, a People‚Äôs Choice Award, a Peabody Award, a D.W. Griffiths Award, and the $50,000 Lincoln Prize.</div>
<div></div>
<div>His next major project, ‚ÄúBaseball,‚Äù covered the entire history of baseball from the 1840‚Äôs to the late 1990‚Äôs. It premiered on PBS in 1994 and became the most watched series in PBS history, with over 45 million viewers. The Daily News said that the series ‚Äúresonates like a Mozart symphony.‚Äù</div>
<div></div>
<div>Ken continued to produce and direct critically acclaimed historical documentaries, ‚ÄúThe West,‚Äù Thomas Jefferson,‚Äù ‚ÄúLewis and Clark: The Journey of the Corps of Discovery,‚Äù ‚ÄúFrank Lloyd Wright,‚Äù ‚ÄúNot for Ourselves Alone: The Story of Elizabeth Cady Stanton &amp; Susan B. Anthony.‚Äù</div>
<div></div>
<div>In 2001, Ken directed his third epic documentary, ‚ÄúJazz,‚Äù which traced the American art form‚Äôs transformations through the decades. Tom Brokaw said, ‚Äú‚ÄôJazz‚Äô is a masterpiece of American television.‚Äù Jack Newfield of the New York Post said, ‚ÄúJazz is the best American documentary film I have ever seen. Period.‚Äù</div>
<div></div>
<div>Ken‚Äôs second war film, ‚ÄúThe War‚Äù aired on PBS in 2007. This poignant feature on World War II follows the lives of four people throughout the U.S. who were all affected by the devastation.</div>
<div></div>
<div>His most recent project, ‚ÄúThe National Parks: America‚Äôs Best Idea‚Äù will air on PBS September, 2009 in six episodes.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Ken was born in Brooklyn, New York in 1953. He currently resides in New Hampshire with his family.</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:9:"Ken Burns";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:9:"ken-burns";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-26 11:14:03";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-26 15:14:03";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=166";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:153;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"574";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-12-18 17:29:09";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-12-18 17:29:09";s:12:"post_content";s:2575:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>Ken Wells is a journalist and novelist who grew up in a snake-collecting family on the banks of the Bayou Black, LA., deep in Cajun country.¬† He began his writing career as a 19-year-old college dropout covering car wrecks and gator sightings for his semiweekly hometown paper, the Houma Courier.¬† He eventually got his B.A. in English and left the bayous in 1975 for the University of Missouri School of Journalism, graduating with honors from the master's program in 1977.</div>
<div></div>
<div>He went on to the Miami Herald where in 1982 he was a finalist for the Pulitzer Prize for a series on how a multibillion-dollar draining system serving agribusiness was helping decimate parts of the Everglades. Wells joined The Wall Street Journal that same year in it's San Francisco bureau and roamed the West covering stories as disparate as polygamy in Utah and the Exxon Valdez Alaska oil spill, and contributing regularly to the paper's popular Page One "middle column" feature. He moved to the London bureau in 1990, in time to help out with the paper's reportage of the first Persian Gulf War. He traveled widely in Africa and wrote extensively about South Africa's transition to a nonradical democracy.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Wells transferred to New York in 1993, where he joined the paper's Page One staff as a writer and editor, eventually running a team of reporters that wrote exclusively for the front page. Two of his team, Tony Horwitz and Angelo Henderson, went on to win Pulitzer Prizes. Ken left the paper in October 2006 after 24 years to join Conde Nast Portfolio as a senior editor. Wells' literary commitment to his bayou home runs deep. He is the author of four well-received novels of Cajun Louisiana: Meely LaBauve, Junior's Leg, Logan's Storm, and Crawfish Mountain, a picaresque satire of political skullduggery and Big Oil shenanigans in the Louisiana wetlands. He is also editor of two anthologies of Journal "middle column stories," Floating Off the Page and Herd on the Street.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Ken Wells is an <a href="http://macmillanspeakers.com/topic/Adventure">adventure keynote speaker</a> and also gives speeches spanning <a href="http://macmillanspeakers.com/topic/Business">Business</a>, <a href="http://macmillanspeakers.com/topic/EnvironmentalIssues">Environment </a>and <a href="http://macmillanspeakers.com/topic/Humor">Humor</a>. You may also want to browse our other <a href="http://macmillanspeakers.com/topic/Humor">humorous keynote speakers</a>.</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:9:"Ken Wells";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:9:"ken-wells";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-26 11:20:06";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-26 15:20:06";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=574";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:154;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"450";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 04:24:37";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 04:24:37";s:12:"post_content";s:1638:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>
<div>Ken Roman is a former Chairman/CEO of Ogilvy &amp; Mather Worldwide, the highly regarded advertising and communications firm founded by David Ogilvy.¬† He joined the firm in 1963 as an assistant account executive and served as Chairman from 1985 to 1989.</div>
<div></div>
<div>In his 26 years with the company, he worked with major clients including American Express, Unilever, Kimberly-Clark and General Foods, and grew its international network and creative reputation.¬† Before O&amp;M he worked in several corporate communications positions.</div>
<div></div>
<div>After leaving O&amp;M in 1989, he joined American Express in a senior communications position for a brief stint before becoming a consultant, board director and author.¬† He was a senior advisor to Price Waterhouse and served on a number of boards (notably Compaq Computer, Brunswick, Gartner) and nonprofit boards (The New York Botanical Garden, National Organization on Disability).</div>
<div></div>
<div>He is the co-author of two business classics ‚Äì <em>How to Advertise</em> and <em>Writing That Works</em>, both in third editions.¬† Published is January of 2009 is his biography of his former boss, <em>The King of Madison Avenue: David Ogilvy¬†and the Making of Modern Advertising.</em></div>
<div></div>
<div>A graduate of Dartmouth College (Editor of the daily newspaper), he was born in Boston, lives in New York, is married to a native New Yorker, and escapes with her to Nantucket.¬† He plays racquet sports and golf, and regards gardening as a competitive sport.</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:13:"Kenneth Roman";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:13:"kenneth-roman";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-05-29 09:22:24";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-29 13:22:24";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=450";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:155;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"400";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:24:35";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:24:35";s:12:"post_content";s:681:"Kevin E. O‚ÄôConnor is¬†a¬†Certified Speaking Professional¬†and one of less than 570 people¬†in the world who hold this honor for speaking and presenting excellence. A renowned expert in his field, he¬†specializes in technical professionals charged with leading teams of their former peers. These include scientists, engineers, pharmaceutical leaders, physician executives, and healthcare professionals as well as any executive who needs to lead teams and present complicated data in an interesting and engaging manner for action and impact. He holds three masters degrees, and also teaches at Chicago‚Äôs Loyola University and Columbia College, Chicago‚Äôs performing arts school.";s:10:"post_title";s:17:"Kevin E. O'Connor";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:15:"kevin-e-oconnor";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-03 15:43:40";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-03 19:43:40";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=400";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:156;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"274";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 21:42:22";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 21:42:22";s:12:"post_content";s:804:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
