</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:15:"Monica Reinagel";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:15:"monica-reinagel";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-26 16:32:33";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-26 20:32:33";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=438";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:192;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"121";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-12 21:45:21";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-12 21:45:21";s:12:"post_content";s:1452:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>
<div>

Nena Baker is the author of <em>The Body Toxic: How the Hazardous Chemistry of Everyday Things Threatens Our Health and Well-being</em>, an ‚Äúeye-opening expose‚Äù (Seattle Post Intelligencer) that sifts through the latest findings about the hazards of everyday chemicals in consumer products. The Washington Post heralded¬†the book¬†as ‚Äúilluminating and consumer-oriented,‚Äù and Baker pulls no punches in her analysis of the corporate irresponsibility and regulatory failures that have created an environmental and public health crisis no less sweeping than global climate change. Baker speaks frequently about the topic of her book as a keynoter and panelist.

Formerly an investigative reporter at The Arizona Republic and The (Portland) Oregonian, Baker is known for hard-hitting stories. Her reports about factories in Indonesia where Nike sneakers are made helped spur the shoe giant to reconsider its responsibilities and led to numerous improvements for workers in the 1990's. Earlier in her career, Baker was a financial reporter and editor for United Press International in New York. She was a Davenport Business Journalism Fellow at the University of Missouri and was recipient of a Pew Center grant for a series of stories about non-voters. She is a graduate of Lewis &amp; Clark College in Portland, Oregon, where she currently makes her home.

</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:10:"Nena Baker";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:10:"nena-baker";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-03 16:07:57";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-03 20:07:57";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=121";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:193;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"306";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 23:04:12";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 23:04:12";s:12:"post_content";s:686:"<div>Neville Isdell was a key player at Coca-Cola for more than 30 years, retiring in 2009 as CEO after regilding the tarnished brand image of the world‚Äôs leading soft-drink company.</div>
<div></div>
<div>He moved to Zambia when he was ten years old and it was there that his life with Coca-Cola really took off.¬†He was the¬†general manager for Johnnesburg, Africa's Coca-Cola Bottling. He continued to work his way up the coporate ladder and his job took him to Australia and then the Philippines until he became president of the company's Central European Division in Germany. After serving as Coke's CEO, board director and chairman, Isdell stepped down as¬†CEO¬†in 2008.</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:14:"Neville Isdell";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:14:"neville-isdell";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-26 16:37:07";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-26 20:37:07";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=306";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:194;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"924";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"3";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-04-29 16:02:50";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-04-29 16:02:50";s:12:"post_content";s:2071:"Named in Esquire Magazine as one of America‚Äôs ‚Äúbest and brightest,‚Äù Nicco Mele is a leading expert in social media integration, Internet marketing, and utilizing online trends within politics, business, and communications. As the webmaster for Governor Howard Dean‚Äôs 2004 presidential race, Mele and the campaign team pioneered for the use of technology and social media¬† in a way that revolutionized political fundraising and American politics. Later that year, Mele founded EchoDitto, the leading web strategy consulting company through which he continues to consult with Fortune 500 companies and nonprofit groups such as the Clinton Foundation, Google, the Sierra Club, Greenpeace, and Barack Obama‚Äôs successful Senate campaign.

&nbsp;

He is also the co-founder of GeniusRocket.com, which uses the Internet to change the world of advertising by soliciting online in an open and collaborative process, and ProxyDemocracy.com, an online resource that gathers and analyzes data on proxy voting behavior.

&nbsp;

In Mele‚Äôs book, <i>The End of Big: How the Internet Makes David the New Goliath</i>, he argues that ‚Äúradical connectivity‚Äù ‚Äì our ability to send vast amounts of data instantly, constantly, and globally ‚Äì is altering our daily lives and reshaping large institutions with dramatic speed. ¬≠¬≠¬≠

&nbsp;

Now an adjunct faculty member at Harvard‚Äôs Kennedy School, Mele teaches graduate level classes on the Internet and its impact on institutions. In 2009, he was named the Spring 2009 Visiting Edward R. Murrow Distinguished Lecturer at the Harvard Shorenstein Center for the study of Press, Politics, and Public Policy.

&nbsp;

Nicco Mele has appeared numerous times as a commentator on CNN, NPR, BBC, CBS Radio, and the Associated Press discussing issues of politics and technology. A highly sought-after speaker, he has been welcomed by audiences at conferences like Silicon Valley Human Rights Conference, US-Islamic World Forum, Personal Democracy Forum, Abu Dhabi Emerging Leaders, AARP, and the United Nations.";s:10:"post_title";s:10:"Nicco Mele";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:10:"nicco-mele";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-21 15:35:39";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-21 19:35:39";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=924";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:195;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"236";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 16:04:28";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 16:04:28";s:12:"post_content";s:1726:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>

A native of Italy, P.M. Forni is a Professor of Italian Literature at Johns Hopkins University, where he heads the Civility Initiative and where he has been recognized with awards for outstanding teaching. He is a graduate of the University of Pavia and received his Ph.D at UCLA.

He has published widely on Italian literary icon Giovanni Boccaccio (1313-1375). In 1997 he co-founded the Johns Hopkins Civility Project, an aggregate of academic and community outreach activities aimed at assessing the importance of manners, civility and politeness in contemporary societies. In 2000 he founded the Civility Initiative at Johns Hopkins. Professor Forni was a Fellow at Villa I Tatti, the Harvard Center for Italian Renaissance Studies in Florence. Also in Florence, he directed the academic program of the Charles S. Singleton Center for Italian Renaissance Studies at Villa Spelman.

His book <em>Choosing Civility: The Twenty-Five Rules of Considerate Conduct</em>¬†has sold more than 100,000 copies.¬†It has been called a¬†"simple, practical, perfectly measured, and quietly magical handbook on the lost art of civility and compassion", and was¬†featured on Oprah. His most recent book is <em>The Civility Solution: What To Do When People Are Rude.</em>¬†Recommended as a "fabulous book" by¬†Peggy Post, director of the Emily Post Institute, it is a thoughtful and practical discussion of the importance of civility in today's hectic world. Reports on his work have appeared in, among others, The New York Times, The Washington Post, The Los Angeles Times, The Wall Street Journal, The Times of London, the Corriere della Sera, and O Magazine.

</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:10:"P.M. Forni";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:9:"p-m-forni";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-26 16:42:43";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-26 20:42:43";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=236";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:196;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"385";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 02:55:00";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 02:55:00";s:12:"post_content";s:2107:"Studies show that most of us encounter up to 200 lies a day, and strangers lie to each other about three times within the first 10 minutes of meeting. Pamela Meyer set out on a several-year journey to research and combat the deception epidemic in her daily life, and her astonishing resulting TED Global Talk, "How to Spot a Liar", has since drawn over a million views. A graduate of Harvard‚Äôs MBA program, CEO and founder of the successful business incubation and development firm Simpatico Networks, Pamela Meyer was inspired by a scientific presentation on the behaviors of deceptive people, and shocked that the huge body of research on deception had not reached the business world. The author of the bestselling <em>Liespotting: Proven Techniques to Detect Deception</em>, Meyer has made it her mission to help people become more accurate at getting to the truth. She believes that‚Äîwith our increasing lack face-to-face interaction, and the deception we have come to expect from everyone, from politicians to television networks‚Äîeverything a CIA operative knows about deception should be familiar to you too, and you too can go from liespotting to truth seeking and finally, building trust. The techniques Meyer teaches are pertinent to any business executive expected to identify the truth in high-stakes situations, and in any corporate environment where the truth is an essential part of business‚Äîmanagers, lawyers, and investment, insurance and medical professionals can all benefit from Meyer‚Äôs tools for better buying, protecting, interviewing, and negotiating.Through her private consulting firm, Pamela Meyer trains corporate executives to read facial micro-expressions and teaches advanced interrogation techniques, body language analysis, and behavior elicitation techniques. Meyer is a Certified Fraud Examiner and also holds an MA in Public Policy from Claremont Graduate School. Her non-stop presentations combine extensive training and research with the soft skills and business acumen that keep them interactive and packed with valuable takeaways for you and your organization.";s:10:"post_title";s:12:"Pamela Meyer";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:12:"pamela-meyer";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-05-29 12:25:31";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-29 16:25:31";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=385";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:197;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"454";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 04:29:15";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 04:29:15";s:12:"post_content";s:934:"PATRICIA ROSSI<strong> </strong>is an etiquette expert and author of <em>Everyday Etiquette: How to Navigate 101 Common and Uncommon Social Situations (St. Martin‚Äôs Griffin, 2011)</em>. She is a sought-after etiquette coach, public speaker, and television and radio personality.

Rossi is ‚ÄúNBC Daytime‚Äôs‚Äù national manners correspondent. Her weekly television segment ‚ÄúManners Minute‚Äù, for which she is both the writer and on air talent, has been airing on NBC, CBS, Fox, and ABC affiliates since 2006. She has been featured in publications such as <em>USA Today, Guideposts, Real Simple, </em>and <em>Parade Magazine</em>. In addition to her television segment, Rossi also writes ‚ÄúManners Express,‚Äù a monthly column for <em>Prestige Magazine </em>

and she is the #1 rated Etiquette Professional Worldwide on Twitter.

Rossi is a graduate of the University of South Florida and the Protocol School of Washington.";s:10:"post_title";s:14:"Patricia Rossi";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:14:"patricia-rossi";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-05-29 10:50:36";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-29 14:50:36";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=454";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:198;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"162";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 13:55:18";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 13:55:18";s:12:"post_content";s:2476:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>
<div>Patrick Buchanan has been a senior advisor to three Presidents, a two-time candidate for the Republican presidential nomination, and was the presidential nominee of the Reform Party in 2000.</div>
<div></div>
<div>From 1966 through 1974, Pat was an assistant to Richard Nixon, and from 1985 to 1987, White House Director of Communications for Ronald Reagan.¬† In 1992,¬†Pat challenged George Bush for the Republican nomination and almost upset the President in the New Hampshire primary.¬†In 1996, he won the New Hampshire primary and finished second to Sen. Dole with three million Republican votes.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Born in Washington, D.C., educated at Catholic and Jesuit schools, Pat received his master‚Äôs degree in journalism from Columbia in 1962.¬† At 23, he became the youngest editorial writer on a major newspaper in America, the St. Louis Globe-Democrat.</div>
<div></div>
<div>In 1966,¬†he became the first full-time staffer to Richard Nixon in his legendary comeback.¬† He traveled with the future President in the campaigns of 1966 and 1968, and served as a special assistant through the final days of Watergate. On leaving the Ford White House in 1974,¬†Pat became a syndicated columnist and founding member of three of the most enduring ‚Äì if not endearing ‚Äì talk shows in television history: NBC‚Äôs The McLaughlin Group, and CNN‚Äôs Capital Gang and Crossfire.</div>
<div></div>
<div>In his White House years,¬†Pat wrote foreign policy speeches, and attended four summits, including Nixon‚Äôs historic opening to China in 1972, and Ronald Reagan‚Äôs Reykjavik summit in 1986 with Mikhail Gorbachev.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Pat¬†has written ten books, including six straight New York Times best sellers: <em>A Republic, Not an Empire; The Death of the West; Where the Right Went Wrong; State of Emergency; Day of Reckoning,</em> and <em>Churchill, Hitler and The Unnecessary War</em>.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Pat¬†is currently a columnist, political analyst for MSNBC, chairman of The American Cause foundation and an editor of The American Conservative.¬† He is married to the former Shelley Ann Scarney, who was a member of the White House Staff from 1969 to 1975.</div>
</div>
</div>
<input id="ctl00_cphMainContent_imgHideFullDesc" type="image" alt="Hide full bio" name="ctl00$cphMainContent$imgHideFullDesc" src="http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/images/up_arrow.gif" />";s:10:"post_title";s:19:"Patrick J. Buchanan";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:18:"patrick-j-buchanan";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-26 16:49:49";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-26 20:49:49";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=162";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:199;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"973";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"3";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-05-02 17:04:32";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-02 17:04:32";s:12:"post_content";s:2217:"<i>New York Times</i> bestselling author Patti Callahan Henry has published nine novels: <i>Losing the Moon</i>, <i>Where the River Runs</i>, <i>When Light Breaks</i>, <i>Between the Tides</i>, <i>The Art of Keeping Secrets</i>, <i>Driftwood Summer</i>, <i>The Perfect Love Song</i>, <i>Coming up for Air</i> and the upcoming <i>And Then I Found You</i>‚Äîwhich will be released by St. Martin‚Äôs Press in April 2013.¬†Hailed as a fresh new voice in southern fiction, Henry has been shortlisted for the Townsend Prize for Fiction, and nominated four different times for the Southeastern Independent Booksellers Novel of the Year. Her work is published in five languages and in audiobook by Brilliance Audio.

&nbsp;

Henry has appeared in numerous magazines including <i>Good Housekeeping</i>, <i>skirt!</i> magazine, <i>South </i>magazine, and <i>Southern Living</i>. Two of her novels were Okra Picks and <i>Coming up For Air</i> was selected for the August 2011 Indie Next List. She is a frequent speaker at fundraisers, library events and book festivals. A full time writer, wife, and mother of three‚ÄîHenry lives in Mountain Brook, Alabama.

&nbsp;

Patti Callahan Henry grew up in Philadelphia, the daughter of an Irish minister, and moved south with her family when she was 12 years old. With the idea that being a novelist was ‚Äúunrealistic,‚Äù she set her sights on becoming a pediatric nurse, graduating from Auburn University with a degree in nursing, and from Georgia State with a Master‚Äôs degree in Child Health. She left nursing to raise her first child, Meagan, and not long after having her third child, Rusk, she began writing down the stories that had always been in her head. Henry wrote early in the mornings, before her children woke for the day, but it wasn‚Äôt until Meagan, then six, told her mother that she wanted ‚Äúto be a writer of books‚Äù when she grew up, that Henry realized that writing was her own dream as well. She began taking writing classes at Emory University, attending weekend writers‚Äô conferences, and educating herself about the publishing industry, rising at 4:30 AM to write. Her first book, <i>Losing the Moon</i>, was published in 2004.¬†<i>¬†</i><i></i>";s:10:"post_title";s:20:"Patti Callahan Henry";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:20:"patti-callahan-henry";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-26 17:17:55";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-26 21:17:55";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=973";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:200;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"934";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"3";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-04-29 17:05:29";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-04-29 17:05:29";s:12:"post_content";s:1741:"Paul Lieberman is the author of <i>Gangster Squad</i> and was executive producer of the Warner Bros. film of the same name starring Sean Penn, Josh Brolin, Ryan Gosling and Emma Stone. He spent more than a decade tracking down surviving members of the secretive Los Angeles police squad given the job of driving Mickey Cohen and other hoodlums out of L.A. in the years after World War II, the Noir era that still defines the so-called City of Angels.

&nbsp;

Lieberman worked for 24 years as an editor and writer for the <i>Los Angeles Times</i> and before that as Projects Editor of <i>The Atlanta Journal-Constitution</i>. He has specialized in long-term investigations into topics as diverse as a hospital serial killer (‚ÄúThe Graveyard Shift‚Äù), a bungled effort by the Boston mob to infiltrate Hollywood (‚ÄúThe Gang that Couldn‚Äôt Shoot Straight‚Äù), and how heiress Doris Duke came to leave her fortune in the hands of her butler (‚ÄúSeeking the Soul of the Billion Dollar Butler‚Äù). He also spent a decade as the <i>Los Angeles Times</i>‚Äô New York-based roving cultural correspondent‚Äîexploring film, the fine arts and popular culture. His work has won dozens of honors, including the Robert F. Kennedy Awards Grand Prize, the George Polk Award and a Gerald Loeb Award. He also shared in two team Pulitzer Prizes at the <i>Times</i>,<i> </i>as a writer on its coverage of the Los Angeles riots and as an editor of its reporting on the Northridge earthquake.

&nbsp;

A native New Yorker, Lieberman is a Phi Beta Kappa graduate of Williams College and was a Nieman Fellow at Harvard, where he studied law and social history. He lives in Westchester County, New York with his wife Heidi, an elementary school principal.";s:10:"post_title";s:14:"Paul Lieberman";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:14:"paul-lieberman";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-04-29 17:05:29";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-04-29 17:05:29";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=934";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:201;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"356";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 00:18:31";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 00:18:31";s:12:"post_content";s:1396:"<div>Peggy Lipton's overnight success on The Mod Squad made her an instant fashion icon and the "it" girl everyone- from Elvis to Paul McCartney- wanted to date.¬† She was the original and ultimate California girl of the early seventies, dashing through the Hollywood Hills in her red convertible and plunging headlong into both a very active career and a fast-paced social life when the cameras weren't rolling.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Peggy Lipton's passionate and complicated fourteen-year marriage to music impresario Quincy Jones made headlines and changed her life, plunging her into confusion and, later, depression.¬† When the marriage ended, she returned to television, starring in the hit TV series, Twin Peaks.</div>
<div></div>
<div>During the writing of her New York Times bestselling memoir, <em>Breathing Out, </em>Peggy was diagnosed with colon cancer, another struggle that changed her life.¬† She survived the battle, and speaks on the topic frequently.¬† Peggy Lipton's life is rich with stories of the pop culture icons of our times, but she speaks powerfully on her personal struggles and resilience as well.¬† She is a hollywood fixture whose voice is refreshing and unexpected.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Recently appearing in another hit show, Alias, Peggy lipton is the winner of a Golden Globe and twice has been nominated for an Emmy.¬† She lives in Los Angeles.</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:12:"Peggy Lipton";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:12:"peggy-lipton";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2012-11-14 00:18:31";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 00:18:31";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=356";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:202;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"506";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 13:44:25";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 13:44:25";s:12:"post_content";s:2417:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>Phil Southerland was diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes when he was only seven months old. Doctors told his mother that he would probably lose his eyesight by the age of 20. Contrary to the doctors‚Äô predictions, Phil is still reading, racing, and keeping his A1C under control through diet, exercise, and an insulin regimen.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Phil began competitive racing in 1994, at the age of 13. He met Joe Eldridge, a fellow passionate cyclist and competitor in college, and the two founded Team Type 1 in 2004. They wanted to prove to the world that people with Type 1 diabetes were capable of racing just as well as ‚Äúnormal‚Äù people. In 2006, Team Type 1 competed in the highly competitive and demanding Race Across America (RAAM), winning the first of two corporate team division titles. They did it again the following year, cycling over 3,000 miles in just over five days.</div>
<div></div>
<div>His career highlights include placing first in the Southeastern Conference Criterium Championships, 8th in the U.S. Junior National Criterium Championships, 9th in the Under 23 U.S. National Road Championships, and 12th in the U.S. Collegiate National Criterium Championships.</div>
<div></div>
<div>In 2008, Phil underwent iliac artery surgery to his left leg, cutting his season short. However, he still holds great aspirations for Team Type 1. He hopes to earn a spot for Team Type 1 in the Tour de France by 2012. He would also like to see a group health insurance plan for people with diabetes in the future.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Phil currently resides in Atlanta, GA. He actively maintains a blog, and is often featured in articles of various publications.</div>
Phil Southerland ¬†is available as a¬†<a href="http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/topic/InspirationalSpeakers"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">inspirational ¬†keynote speaker</span></a>¬†from our¬†<a href="http://macmillanspeakers.com/"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">keynote speakers bureau</span></a>. You may also be interested in our other¬†<a href="http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/topic/Leadership"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">leadership speakers</span></a>, as well as our experts on¬†<a href="http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/topic/HealthWellness"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Health and Wellness</span></a>.

</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:16:"Phil Southerland";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:16:"phil-southerland";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-27 09:53:06";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-27 13:53:06";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=506";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:203;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:4:"1114";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"3";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-06-11 12:51:13";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-11 16:51:13";s:12:"post_content";s:1059:"Botsman writes, speakers, and consults on the power of collaboration and sharing through network technologies, as well as how it will transform business, consumerism, and the way we live, work and consume. In 2010, TIME Magazine called collaborative consumption one of the ‚Äú10 Ideas That Will Change the World.‚Äù She is the founder of <a href="http://cclab.collaborativeconsumption.com/">Collaborative Lab</a>, which helps businesses and governments worldwide to understand and harness the power and potential of collaborative consumption.

&nbsp;

Her articles on the relationship between technology and human behavior have been published in Harvard Business Review, The Economist, CNN, New York Times, and other publications. Botsman is also a contributing editor for WIRED UK and has a tech trends column in the Australian Financial Review.

&nbsp;

Recently, Botsman was named a 2013 Young Global Leader by the World Economic Forum, an honor that recognizes individuals for their achievements and commitment to improving the state of the world.";s:10:"post_title";s:14:"Rachel Botsman";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:54:"global-thought-leader-and-founder-of-collaborative-lab";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-11 12:54:54";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-11 16:54:54";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:63:"http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=1114";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:204;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"554";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-12-18 16:47:42";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-12-18 16:47:42";s:12:"post_content";s:1113:"Dr. Vreeman is an assistant professor of pediatrics in the Children‚Äôs Health Services Research Program at the Indiana University School of Medicine and a pediatrician at Riley Hospital for Children.¬† In addition, she is co-director of pediatric research for the Academic Model Providing Access to Healthcare, an academic collaboration that provides comprehensive HIV treatment for over 80,000 patients in Kenya.¬† Dr. Vreeman is also an affiliated scientist at the Regenstrief Institute and a faculty investigator with the Center for Health Policy and Professionalism Research.¬† Dr. Vreeman‚Äôs research work focuses on the development of instruments to improve children‚Äôs health care within resource-limited settings.
<div></div>
<div>She received her MD from Michigan State University College of Human Medicine, and completed her internship, residency, and a chief residency in pediatrics at the Indiana University School of Medicine.¬† She also completed a fellowship in Children‚Äôs Health Services Research and a masters degree in clinical research at the Indiana University School of Medicine.</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:18:"Rachel Vreeman, MD";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:17:"rachel-vreeman-md";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-06-27 09:55:52";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-06-27 13:55:52";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=554";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:205;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"309";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 23:09:17";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 23:09:17";s:12:"post_content";s:1223:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
