&nbsp;

However, it was after three more novels before she began to grasp Literature properly ‚Äì resulting in her NYT bestseller, <i>Z: A Novel of Zelda Fitzgerald</i>. Fowler felt compelled to write a story that should bring a maligned, talented, and troubled woman the justice she deserves, instead of her reputation as ‚ÄúF. Scott Fitzgerald‚Äôs crazy, disruptive wife.‚Äù";s:10:"post_title";s:19:"Therese Anne Fowler";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:19:"therese-anne-fowler";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-05-09 18:46:21";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-09 18:46:21";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:63:"http://www.macmillanspeakers.com/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=1008";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:249;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"479";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 12:58:40";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 12:58:40";s:12:"post_content";s:3102:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">

Thom Shanker, Pentagon correspondent for <em>The New York Times</em>, routinely spends time embedded with troops in Iraq and Afghanistan. Shanker was formerly a foreign editor and correspondent for the <em>Chicago Tribune</em>, based in Moscow, Berlin, and Sarajevo. He is co-author, with Eric Schmitt, of <em>Counterstrike: The Untold Story of America‚Äôs Secret Campaign Against Al Qaeda</em>.
Shanker joined¬†<em>The Times</em>¬†in 1997 as assistant Washington editor, responsible for managing the newspaper‚Äôs coverage of foreign policy, national security and economics from the Washington bureau. He was named Pentagon correspondent in May of 2001 and has since then covered military affairs and national security strategy, including efforts at transformation within the Pentagon and the global campaign against terrorism. He embedded with Army Special Forces at Kandahar for the war in Afghanistan, and has also conducted numerous reporting trips to Iraq, embedding in the field with units from the company level through battalion, brigade, division and corps.
Prior to joining¬†<em>The Times</em>, Shanker¬†was foreign editor of¬†the <em>Chicago Tribune</em>. He was the <em>Tribune</em>‚Äôs¬†senior European correspondent, based in Berlin, from 1992 to1995, and spent most of that time covering the wars in former Yugoslavia, where he was the first reporter to uncover and write about the Serb campaign of systematic mass rape of Muslim women. He also wrote about European integration, NATO policy, nuclear smuggling and the withdrawal of American, British, French and Russian troops from Berlin following the reunification of the German capital.

As¬†the <em>Tribune</em>‚Äôs¬†Moscow bureau chief from 1985 to 1988, Shanker covered the first years of the Gorbachev era as well as issues of superpower arms control. From 1988 to 1990, he was¬†the <em>Tribune</em>‚Äôs¬†Pentagon correspondent. Mr. Shanker returned to Moscow from 1990 to 1992 to cover the death of the USSR and the collapse of the communist empire in Eastern Europe. He also spent one year as the foreign and military affairs writer on the <em>Tribune</em>‚Äôs editorial board. He has been published in¬†<em>The New York Times¬†Sunday Magazine</em>,¬†<em>The New York Review of Books</em>,¬†<em>The New Republic</em>, <em>American Journalism Review</em>¬†and <em>Military Review</em>, and contributed to the Norton anthology <em>Crimes of War: What the Public Should Know</em>. He also is a member of the Council on Foreign Relations. Thom Shanker researched and wrote <em>Counterstrike</em> as a writer-in-residence with Eric Schmitt at the Center for a New American Security.
Shanker attended the master‚Äôs degree program at The Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University, specializing in strategic nuclear policy and international law, and passing his master‚Äôs orals with Highest Honors. He graduated <em>cum laude</em> with a B.A. in political science from Colorado College, and was awarded an Honorary Doctor of Laws by the college in 2004.

</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:12:"Thom Shanker";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:12:"thom-shanker";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2012-11-14 12:58:40";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 12:58:40";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=479";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:250;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:2:"60";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-10-25 13:48:38";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-10-25 13:48:38";s:12:"post_content";s:629:"Mr. Oliphant has been a correspondent for The Boston Globe since 1968 and its Washington columnist since 1989. He is a native of Brooklyn, a product of La Jolla High School in California and a 1967 graduate of Harvard. He was one of three editors on special assignment who managed The Globe's coverage of Boston's traumatic school desegregation, which was awarded the Pulitzer Prize in 1975. He has also won the writing award given by the American Society of Newspaper Editors. He has appeared on ABC's Nightline, The Jim Lehrer News Hour, Face The Nation, The Today Show, Good Morning America and CBS This Morning.¬† He has been";s:10:"post_title";s:15:"Thomas Oliphant";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:15:"thomas-oliphant";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:28:18";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:28:18";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:61:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=60";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:251;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"186";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-13 14:33:07";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 14:33:07";s:12:"post_content";s:1071:"Thurston Clarke is the bestselling author of¬†eleven widely acclaimed works of history, biography, travel literature, and fiction. His account of the 1968 campaign of Robert F. Kennedy, <em>The Last Campaign</em>, was on the hardcover nonfiction New York Times bestseller list for five weeks and was chosen by Amazon as a best book of 2008. Three of his other books have been New York Times notable books. The rights to his <em>The Last Campaign</em> have been acquired¬† for a major feature film about Robert F. Kennedy. His book <em>Pearl Harbor Ghosts</em> was the basis of a major prime-time CBS News documentary,¬†for which¬†he was the principal on-camera narrator. His bestselling <em>Lost Hero</em>, a biography of Raoul Wallenberg, was made into an award-winning NBC miniseries. His articles have appeared in Vanity Fair, Glamour, The New York Times, The Washington Post, and numerous other publications. He is the recipient of a Guggenheim Fellowship and a Lowell Thomas Award for travel literature. He lives in the Adirondacks with his wife and three daughters.";s:10:"post_title";s:15:"Thurston Clarke";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:15:"thurston-clarke";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2012-11-13 14:33:07";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-13 14:33:07";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=186";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:252;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"462";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 12:33:29";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 12:33:29";s:12:"post_content";s:1860:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>
<div>Tim Sanders stands for strong business relationships, both internal and external. ‚ÄúGet them right,‚Äù he says, ‚Äúand you‚Äôll grow your business during good and bad times alike.‚Äù His relevant point of view makes him one of the most in demand speakers on the conference and convention circuit.</div>
<div>
His first book, <em>Love Is the Killer App: How To Win Business and Influence Friends</em> is a New York Times and international business best seller. It stresses the importance of knowledge sharing, networking and compassion. His follow up, <em>The Likeability Factor </em>explains the concept of emotional talent and the importance of creating an engaging experience.</div>
<div>
His newest book, <em>Saving The World At Work</em>, examines the external relationship between a business and society. In it, he argues that social responsibility and sustainability are hotbeds for business innovation. Companies that focus on these areas will attract new customers as well as boost the morale of employees and partners. Along the way, they‚Äôll save money too!</div>
<div>
Tim has deep experience in cutting-edge businesses and marketing. He‚Äôs weathered the quality movement as well as the dotcom crash and emerged with precious insight. He was the Chief Solutions Officer at Yahoo! and later its Leadership Coach. Prior to his senior positions at Yahoo!, Tim created and led the Yahoo! ValueLab, an in-house ‚Äúthink tank‚Äù which delivered futuristic insight on technology and human behavior.</div>
<div>
His work is frequently featured in the media, most recently in The New York Times, Financial Times, The Wall Street Journal and Fast Company.</div>
<div>
He‚Äôs a frequent guest on TV and written about in countless business and industry publications.</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:11:"Tim Sanders";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:11:"tim-sanders";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2012-11-14 12:33:29";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 12:33:29";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=462";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:253;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"111";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-12 21:21:09";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-12 21:21:09";s:12:"post_content";s:3110:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
<div>
<div>
<div>As one of only 41 people in history to have reached both the North and South Poles on foot and a veteran of over a dozen mountain and polar expeditions, Tom Avery is one of the brightest stars amongst the current crop of international explorers.¬† Tom is probably best known for leading the expedition described by the Guinness Book of Records as "the fastest surface journey to the North Pole", which retraced Robert Peary and Matthew Henson‚Äôs footsteps to the "Top of the World."</div>
<div></div>
<div>Tom Avery was born in December 1975 in London, England and was brought up in Brazil and France.¬† His passion for adventure began at the age of eight when he first read about Captain Scott.¬† He knew then that his life wouldn't be complete until he followed his hero‚Äôs footsteps to the South Pole.</div>
<div></div>
<div>Tom took up climbing at age sixteen but it wasn't until university that his expedition career really took off; there, he organized and led expeditions to the Andes, New Zealand, the Alps, Tanzania, Patagonia and Morocco.</div>
<div></div>
<div>After graduating from Bristol University in England 1998 with a degree in Geography and Geology, he began a 15-month career as an accountant with Arthur Andersen.¬† Eventually forced to choose between the city and the mountains, Tom chose the mountains.</div>
<div></div>
<div>The pinnacle of Tom‚Äôs climbing career to date was in 2000 when he led a pioneering British expedition to a previously unexplored 20-mile mountain range close to China‚Äôs western border.¬† His team scaled nine unnamed virgin summits up to 20,000 feet high.</div>
<div></div>
<div>On December 28, 2002, days after his 27th birthday, Tom Avery became the youngest Briton to complete the perilous journey to the South Pole on foot.¬† His team also broke the South Pole Speed Record; using state of the art kites to power them across the ice, they covered the last 47 miles to the Pole in an amazing 31 hours.</div>
<div></div>
<div>In April 2005 Tom electrified the exploration world by recreating Robert Peary‚Äôs disputed 1909 expedition to the North Pole.¬† The five-strong team travelled in a similar style to Peary with teams of Eskimo dogs and replica wooden sledges.¬† Tom's ambitious aim was to prove the skeptics wrong and match Peary‚Äôs 37-day journey to the Pole.¬† After an epic dash across the most unforgiving environment on the planet, Tom‚Äôs exhausted team rewrote the history books by making it to the Pole with five hours to spare.</div>
<div></div>
<div>A born leader, this remarkable young man runs every expedition himself, organizing everything from the fundraising to the training to the logistics to the selection of his teams.¬† His expeditions have received a huge amount of international print and TV media coverage.¬† Tom's highly acclaimed first book, <em>Pole Dance</em>, was published in 2003.¬† <em>To the End of the Earth</em>, the story about his record-breaking North Pole expedition was published in March 2009.</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>";s:10:"post_title";s:9:"Tom Avery";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:9:"tom-avery";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-05-29 10:06:57";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-05-29 14:06:57";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=111";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:254;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"409";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:35:10";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:35:10";s:12:"post_content";s:364:"Parker Bowles is a food writer with columns in The Mail on Sunday and Tatler. He is the author of E is For Eating-An Alphabet of Greed, The Year of Eating Dangerously (St Martin‚Äôs Press) and the upcoming Full English, the story of how British food lost it‚Äôs way. He also co-presents Market Kitchen on UKTV Food and is a contributor to Gordon Ramsay‚Äôs F Word.";s:10:"post_title";s:17:"Tom Parker Bowles";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:17:"tom-parker-bowles";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:35:10";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:35:10";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=409";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:255;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"415";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:42:23";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:42:23";s:12:"post_content";s:616:"Tom Perrotta is the author of five previous work of fiction: Bad Haircut, The Wishbones, Election, and the New York Times bestselling Joe College and Little Children. Election was made into the acclaimed 1999 movie directed by Alexander Payne and starring Matthew Broderick and Reese Witherspoon. Little Children was released as a movie directed by Todd Field and starring Kate Winslet and Jennifer Connelly in 2006, and for which Perrotta received Golden Globe and Academy Award nominations for best screenplay. His most recent novel, The Leftovers¬† was released in 2011. He lives outside of Boston, Massachusetts.";s:10:"post_title";s:12:"Tom Perrotta";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:6:"closed";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:12:"tom-perrotta";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:42:23";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 03:42:23";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:62:"http://localhost/macmillian_site/?post_type=speaker&#038;p=415";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:7:"speaker";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:256;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"440";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"4";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2012-11-14 04:13:18";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2012-11-14 04:13:18";s:12:"post_content";s:4392:"<div id="ctl00_cphMainContent_divSpeakerDesc">
